<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="stakeholder-analysis">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>ba</group>
    <domain>ba-core</domain>
    <summary>Identify parties affected by change, classify by influence using Mendelow and Mitchell-Agle-Wood models, document needs and concerns, and plan engagement with frozen definitions.</summary>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-26</created>
    <tags>
      <tag>stakeholder</tag>
      <tag>analysis</tag>
      <tag>engagement</tag>
      <tag>bakok</tag>
      <tag>salience</tag>
    </tags>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Stakeholder Analysis</title>
    <summary>Identify parties affected by change initiatives, classify by influence and impact, document needs, and plan engagement. Uses Mendelow grid for cadence and Mitchell-Agle-Wood salience model for prioritization. Definitions must be frozen before any classification begins.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Gathering requirements from the wrong people produces incomplete or conflicting inputs that surface late and cause rework. Formal stakeholder analysis with locked definitions and a responsibility model (RACI/RASCI/DACI/RAPID) gives every downstream artifact a traceable source of truth and satisfies BAKOK 3 §3.2 audit requirements.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Starting any initiative: identify stakeholders before the first interview or workshop</item>
        <item>Regulated / audited programs (SOX, MDR, ISO 13485, GDPR Art. 35 DPIA) needing BAKOK-aligned artifacts</item>
        <item>Onboarding a new BA or agent to an existing program to ensure reproducible classification</item>
        <item>Choosing a responsibility model (RACI vs RASCI vs DACI vs RAPID) for a specific decision class</item>
        <item>Disambiguating "stakeholder" from "user", "persona", "actor", "customer" across Confluence/Notion pages</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Solo / pre-PMF work where ceremony exceeds value — use direct customer discovery</item>
        <item>Pure code refactor with zero business-stakeholder change</item>
        <item>One-shot decisions with a single accountable owner — a one-line ADR is enough</item>
        <item>Open-source community projects with pseudonymous identities (salience axes cannot be measured)</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="step-1-identify-stakeholders">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>List every party who is affected by, has influence over, must approve, will implement, or will use the solution.</statement>
        <rationale>Missing a stakeholder early guarantees conflicting or incomplete requirements arriving late.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <p>Stakeholder categories:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Customer — external beneficiary (end users, buyers)</item>
        <item>End User — direct solution users (employees, customers)</item>
        <item>Sponsor — provides resources or authority (executive, budget owner)</item>
        <item>Domain SME — subject matter expert (process owners, specialists)</item>
        <item>Implementation SME — technical expert (developers, architects)</item>
        <item>Tester — validates solution (QA team, UAT participants)</item>
        <item>Regulator — compliance authority (legal, audit, government)</item>
        <item>Supplier — external provider (vendors, partners)</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="step-2-characterize-each-stakeholder">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Document influence, impact, attitude, knowledge, needs, and communication style for each identified stakeholder.</statement>
        <rationale>Without per-stakeholder attributes, engagement is generic and misses resistance early.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="step-3-map-influence-and-impact">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Place stakeholders on a 2x2 power-interest grid: Manage Closely (high/high), Keep Satisfied (high/low), Keep Informed (low/high), Monitor (low/low).</statement>
        <rationale>Grid quadrant determines engagement cadence and channel; without this, effort is spread evenly across unequal stakeholders.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="step-4-identify-needs-and-concerns">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>For each key stakeholder, record specific needs, concerns, success criteria, and current pain points.</statement>
        <rationale>Stated needs alone are insufficient; unstated concerns drive resistance if not surfaced early.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="step-5-plan-engagement">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Assign an engagement approach (Active/Consult/Inform), frequency, and method to each stakeholder based on their grid quadrant.</statement>
        <rationale>A single plan for all stakeholders wastes sponsor time and under-invests in high-impact resistors.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="step-6-manage-relationships-continuously">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Treat stakeholder analysis as a living activity: re-run the salience classifier after org events (reorg, leadership change, regulatory letter).</statement>
        <rationale>BAKOK 3 explicitly calls stakeholder analysis a continuous activity; static artifacts go stale in 2-6 weeks.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <p>Conflict resolution sequence: understand each position, find common ground, identify trade-offs, escalate to sponsor if needed, document decision with rationale.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="mendelow-power-interest-grid">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use Mendelow for engagement cadence (which quadrant maps to which channel), not for prioritization.</statement>
        <rationale>Mendelow flattens politics to two axes and is silent on legitimacy and urgency; it is a channel selector, not a prioritization model.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Treating Mendelow as the only classification model.</description>
        <reason>It does not capture urgency or legitimacy; a high-power actor without legitimacy is a bully, not a stakeholder — the correct response is escalation, not accommodation.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="mitchell-agle-wood-salience-model">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Apply Mitchell-Agle-Wood (power x legitimacy x urgency) to classify each stakeholder into one of 8 types: dormant, discretionary, demanding, dominant, dangerous, dependent, definitive, non-stakeholder.</statement>
        <rationale>Salience tells you who matters and in what order; Mendelow tells you which channel to use. They are complementary, not substitutes.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Require cited evidence (quote, transcript line, org-chart entry) for every salience axis; return "unknown" if evidence is absent — never infer urgency from tone alone.</statement>
        <rationale>LLM urgency inference from tone is a known failure mode; a regulatory deadline or contractual SLA is the only valid urgency signal.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Classifying legitimacy using Anglo-American corporate norms only.</description>
        <reason>In high-context cultures (JP, KR, parts of EU) and in jurisdictions with statutory bodies (e.g., DE Betriebsrat), legitimacy flows through indirect networks the standard model does not capture.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="responsibility-models">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Pick ONE responsibility model per program before any artifact is produced; document the choice and its rationale.</statement>
        <rationale>RACI, RASCI, DACI, and RAPID use some of the same letters with different meanings; mixing models within a program makes every role assignment ambiguous.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>RACI — steady-state operations: exactly one A per row, one or more R</item>
        <item>RASCI — adds S (Support); use when "support" roles are common (data ops, infra)</item>
        <item>DACI — time-boxed decisions with a single Driver and an Approver</item>
        <item>RAPID — cross-functional decisions with split Input and Agreement roles</item>
      </list>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Enforce RACI integrity mechanically: exactly one Accountable per row, at least one Responsible, no R+A collapse to a single person. Lint in CI.</statement>
        <rationale>Human-edited RACI tables drift toward multiple A entries and R-spam; a linter is cheaper than an audit finding.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="stakeholder-vs-adjacent-concepts">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Keep stakeholder, persona, and actor artifacts strictly separate: a stakeholder row never becomes a persona; an actor (UML) is a system-interaction role with no political weight; a persona has no decision authority.</statement>
        <rationale>Conflating them breaks requirements traceability; a persona that inherits engagement cadence from a stakeholder produces meaningless engagement plans.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Maintain an explicit non-stakeholders list. Documenting exclusions prevents repeated re-litigation of who belongs on the register.</statement>
        <rationale>Without a declared exclusion list, every new team member re-opens the same boundary debates.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="definition-freezing-protocol">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Before classifying any stakeholder, persist a glossary.md and model-choice.md in the program BA folder declaring: stakeholder definition (verbatim from BABOK 3 §3.2 or ISO 21502 §4.4), responsibility model chosen, salience model chosen, and rationale for rejecting alternatives.</statement>
        <rationale>LLMs treat "stakeholder" as a synonym for "user" or "persona" by default; injecting the frozen definition verbatim into the system prompt is the only reliable mitigation.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Sponsor signs the register baseline; subsequent diffs require sponsor acknowledgment only for attitude or accountability changes, not for contact info updates.</statement>
        <rationale>Keeps sign-off lightweight while protecting the high-stakes fields that affect engagement strategy.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="subagent-patterns">
      <list>
        <item>definitions-linter-agent (sonnet) — validates the register against the chosen model; RACI: exactly one A per row; RASCI: at most one A, multiple S allowed; flags violations as PR comments</item>
        <item>salience-classifier-agent (sonnet) — applies Mitchell-Agle-Wood to each stakeholder; emits one of 8 types with citations per axis</item>
        <item>bakok-mapper-agent (sonnet) — maps the register to BAKOK 3 §3.2 deliverables for audit traceability</item>
        <item>password-scrubber-agent — sweeps stakeholder docs for leaked credentials or PII before commit</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="prompt-patterns">
      <example type="good" title="Two-stage prompt: definitions first, classification second">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
STAGE 1 — Definitions agent:
Given the program charter, choose:
- responsibility_model: one of [RACI, RASCI, DACI, RAPID]
- salience_model: one of [Mendelow, Mitchell-Agle-Wood, both]
- stakeholder_definition: verbatim from BAKOK 3 §3.2 OR ISO 21502 §4.4

Emit STRICT JSON:
{ "responsibility_model": "...", "salience_model": "...",
  "stakeholder_definition": "...", "rationale": "<=3 sentences",
  "rejected_alternatives": ["..."] }
Rule: cite the source clause; no invention.

STAGE 2 — Salience classifier:
For each stakeholder in the register, apply Mitchell-Agle-Wood:
- power: ability to impose will (H/M/L + evidence)
- legitimacy: socially accepted claim (H/M/L + evidence)
- urgency: time-criticality of claim (H/M/L + evidence, cite deadline/SLA)
Emit type: dormant|discretionary|demanding|dominant|dangerous|dependent|definitive|non-stakeholder.
Rule: any axis without evidence => "unknown"; do not infer urgency from tone.
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="ai-agent-gotchas">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent silently merges "stakeholder" with "user" or "persona".</description>
        <reason>Default LLM training conflates these; fix by forcing the chosen stakeholder_definition into the system prompt verbatim every call.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent over-assigns R and C in RACI — every role gets something.</description>
        <reason>Constrain output: max 1 A, max 3 R, require one-line rationale per C; validate with the lint script.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent infers urgency from message tone rather than from a cited deadline or SLA.</description>
        <reason>Tone-based urgency is statistically biased; require "urgency_source: deadline/SLA/contractual" and reject entries without it.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>BABOK section citations hallucinate plausible-sounding clause numbers.</description>
        <reason>Maintain a curated bakok-toc.md and constrain the agent to cite only from it.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent auto-publishes the register.</description>
        <reason>Names, attitudes, and salience scores are confidential; one accidental share ends stakeholder trust.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="mandatory-human-in-the-loop-checkpoints">
      <list>
        <item>Freezing definitions and choosing the responsibility model</item>
        <item>Choosing the salience model</item>
        <item>Baselining the register</item>
        <item>Any change to Accountable (A) assignments</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="continuous-stakeholder-management">
      <p>Treat stakeholder analysis as a living activity per BAKOK guidance. Re-run classification after org events: reorg (changes power structure), leadership change (impacts urgency and legitimacy), regulatory letter (introduces new constraints), market disruption, competitive threat, funding event, acquisition/divestiture, major customer win or loss, product pivot, or change in business priorities. Without periodic re-assessment, static registers become liabilities when change happens and stakeholder opposition emerges from parties not flagged as key.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="common-failure-modes">
      <p>Missing the boundary question: "Who is NOT a stakeholder?" Documenting exclusions prevents repeated boundary debates in the next phase — stakeholder lists grow if you do not declare who is not included. Confusing stakeholder with persona or actor. A persona that inherits engagement cadence from a stakeholder row produces meaningless engagement plans. Skipping the formality of defining "stakeholder" before classification. LLMs default to conflating stakeholder with user; the only mitigation is verbatim definition injection into the system prompt. Merging multiple responsibility models in a single program. Using RACI for one decision, DACI for another, RASCI for a third produces ambiguity when roles overlap.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="raci-for-ba-activities">
      <example type="good" title="BA activity responsibility assignments using RACI">
        <code lang="markdown"><![CDATA[
| Activity                | Sponsor | SME | User | BA |
|-------------------------|---------|-----|------|----|
| Define requirements     | A       | C   | R    | R  |
| Approve requirements    | A       | C   | I    | R  |
| Validate solution       | A       | C   | R    | R  |
| Accept delivery         | A       | C   | R    | I  |
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="definition-freezing-and-model-choice">
      <p>Before classifying any stakeholder, persist a glossary.md and model-choice.md in the program BA folder declaring: stakeholder definition (verbatim from BABOK 3 §3.2 or ISO 21502 §4.4), responsibility model chosen (RACI/RASCI/DACI/RAPID), salience model chosen (Mendelow / Mitchell-Agle-Wood / both), and rationale for rejecting alternatives. LLMs treat "stakeholder" as a synonym for "user" or "persona" by default; injecting the frozen definition verbatim into the system prompt every call is the only reliable mitigation.</p>
      <p>Sponsor signs the register baseline; subsequent diffs require sponsor acknowledgment only for attitude or accountability changes, not for contact info updates. Keeps sign-off lightweight while protecting the high-stakes fields that affect engagement strategy.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="recommended-subagents">
      <list>
        <item>definitions-linter-agent (Sonnet) — validates the register against the chosen model. RACI: exactly one A per row. RASCI: at most one A, multiple S allowed. Flags violations as PR comments.</item>
        <item>salience-classifier-agent (Sonnet) — applies Mitchell-Agle-Wood to each stakeholder; emits one of 8 types with citations per axis (power, legitimacy, urgency).</item>
        <item>bakok-mapper-agent (Sonnet) — maps the register to BAKOK 3 §3.2 deliverables for audit traceability.</item>
        <item>password-scrubber-agent — sweeps stakeholder docs for leaked credentials or PII before commit.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="best-practices-and-rules">
      <p>Always require evidence for every salience axis. Return "unknown" if evidence is absent; never infer urgency from tone alone. A regulatory deadline or contractual SLA is the only valid urgency signal. Maintain an explicit non-stakeholders list to prevent repeated re-litigation of who belongs. Document the choice of responsibility model with rationale — never mix RACI and DACI in the same program. Run stakeholder analysis as the very first BA task before any interview. Build stakeholder register in parallel with the charter and business case. Expect 30-50% of initially-identified stakeholders to be reclassified during the first cycle; high re-classification is normal and signals good discovery. Keep the register as a living document; trigger re-analysis quarterly or when org events happen (reorg, regulation change, market shift). Maintain separation between stakeholder register and user personas — a persona is an archetypal user, not a decision-maker. Route engagement plans through the Mendelow grid (which quadrant) and tailor frequency and channel accordingly. Test your salience classifications by running them past the sponsor for gut-check before acting on them.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="cultural-context-and-global-delivery">
      <p>Stakeholder salience and legitimacy flow differently across cultures and jurisdictions. Anglo-American corporate org charts do not capture legitimacy in high-context cultures (Japan, Korea, parts of Europe) where power flows through indirect networks, consensus-building, and relationship history. In jurisdictions with statutory works councils (Germany Betriebsrat, Austria Betriebsrat, Scandinavia) and data protection authorities (GDPR controllers), legitimacy is formal and legal, not organizational hierarchy. Misclassifying a statutory body as low-legitimacy guarantees missed escalation and compliance violations. When building global stakeholder registers, document the jurisdiction-specific legitimacy anchors (corporate hierarchy, statutory body appointment, customer contract, regulatory mandate, SLA commitment) for each row.</p>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/stakeholder-register.md" purpose="Register table for tracking all stakeholders with classifications"/>
      <template path="templates/stakeholder-profile.md" purpose="Per-stakeholder profile template with needs, concerns, and engagement history"/>
      <template path="templates/raci-lint.sh" purpose="Bash linter: fails if any RACI row has != 1 Accountable or 0 Responsible"/>
    </templates>

  </content>
</methodology>
